he commentary contrasts the representations of Rome with Africa and explores the significance of Africa as a space contaminated by evil, but which remains an integral part of Rome. Along with Lucan’s other geographic and natural-scientific discussions, Africa’s position as a part of the Roman world is painstakingly supported by astronomic and geographic erudition in Lucan’s blending of scientific and mythological discourse. The poet is a visionary who supports his truth claims by means of scientific discourse.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEpic poetry, LatinxHistory and criticism. 4aEpik. 4aJulius Caesar. 4aLucan. 4aRömische Geschichte. 4aRömische Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aFlavian Literature.  aJulius Caesar.  aLatin Epic.  aLiterature).  aLucanus, M. Annaeus.  aRome (History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Classics and Near East Studies 2000-2014 (EN)z978311062109908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Classics and Near East Studies 2000 - 2014z9783110636178oZDB-23-GCN08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2009z9783110219517oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2009z978311021952408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET ALTERTUM 2009z9783110219456oZDB-23-DGD0 cprintz978311020385140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311021651640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110216516423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110216516/original  a978-3-11-021952-4  E-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2009b2009 